# Jido Composer Demo

```elixir
Mix.install(
  [
    {:jido_composer, path: Path.join(__DIR__, "..")},
    {:kino, "~> 0.14"}
  ],
  config: [
    jido_action: [default_timeout: :timer.minutes(5)]
  ]
)
```

## Introduction

**Jido Composer** provides two composition patterns for building agent flows:

1. **Workflow** -- Deterministic FSM-based pipelines. Each state binds to an action or sub-agent.
   Transitions are fully determined by outcomes (no LLM decisions).

2. **Orchestrator** -- An agent that uses an LLM to freely compose available sub-agents
   and actions at runtime via a ReAct loop.

Both share a **Node** abstraction -- a uniform `context -> context` interface -- and support
arbitrary nesting.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph Node Abstraction
        AN[ActionNode] --> N[Node Interface]
        FN[FanOutNode] --> N
        HN[HumanNode] --> N
        AgN[AgentNode] --> N
    end

    subgraph Composition Patterns
        N --> W[Workflow FSM]
        N --> O[Orchestrator ReAct]
    end

    W -->|deterministic| R1[Scoped Context Result]
    O -->|LLM-driven| R2[Final Answer]
```

**What you'll learn:**

1. Linear workflows with scoped context accumulation
2. Branching on custom action outcomes
3. Parallel execution with FanOutNode
4. Human-in-the-loop with suspend/resume and live FSM visualization
5. LLM-driven orchestration (requires API key)
6. Composing workflows inside orchestrators
7. AgentNode: nesting an orchestrator inside a workflow
8. Multi-agent domain modeling pipeline

## Setup

An Anthropic API key is required for the orchestrator demos (5-8).

```elixir
api_key =
  System.get_env("ANTHROPIC_API_KEY") ||
    raise "ANTHROPIC_API_KEY environment variable is required. Set it in your Livebook app settings."

Application.put_env(:req_llm, :anthropic_api_key, api_key)
Kino.Markdown.new("**API key configured.**")
```

## Define Demo Actions

All actions are defined inline so this notebook is fully self-contained.

```elixir
defmodule Demo.AddAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "add",
    description: "Adds an amount to a value",
    schema: [
      value: [type: :float, required: true, doc: "The current value"],
      amount: [type: :float, required: true, doc: "The amount to add"]
    ]

  def run(%{value: value, amount: amount}, _context) do
    {:ok, %{result: value + amount}}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.MultiplyAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "multiply",
    description: "Multiplies a value by an amount",
    schema: [
      value: [type: :float, required: true, doc: "The current value"],
      amount: [type: :float, required: true, doc: "The multiplier"]
    ]

  def run(%{value: value, amount: amount}, _context) do
    {:ok, %{result: value * amount}}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.EchoAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "echo",
    description: "Echoes a message string",
    schema: [
      message: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Message to echo"]
    ]

  def run(%{message: message}, _context) do
    {:ok, %{echoed: message}}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.ExtractAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "extract",
    description: "Simulates data extraction from a source",
    schema: [
      source: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Data source identifier"]
    ]

  def run(%{source: source}, _context) do
    {:ok, %{records: [%{id: 1, source: source}, %{id: 2, source: source}], count: 2}}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.TransformAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "transform",
    description: "Uppercases source field in extracted records",
    schema: [
      extract: [type: :map, required: false, doc: "Results from extract step"]
    ]

  def run(params, _context) do
    records = get_in(params, [:extract, :records]) || []

    transformed =
      Enum.map(records, fn rec ->
        Map.update(rec, :source, "", &String.upcase/1)
      end)

    {:ok, %{records: transformed, count: length(transformed)}}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.LoadAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "load",
    description: "Simulates loading records into storage",
    schema: [
      transform: [type: :map, required: false, doc: "Results from transform step"]
    ]

  def run(params, _context) do
    records = get_in(params, [:transform, :records]) || []
    {:ok, %{loaded: length(records), status: :complete}}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.ValidateOutcomeAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "validate_outcome",
    description: "Returns custom outcomes based on data validity",
    schema: [
      data: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Data to validate"]
    ]

  def run(%{data: "valid"}, _context), do: {:ok, %{validated: true, quality: :good}}
  def run(%{data: "invalid"}, _context), do: {:ok, %{validated: false, quality: :bad}, :invalid}
  def run(%{data: "retry"}, _context), do: {:ok, %{validated: false, quality: :unstable}, :retry}
  def run(%{data: _}, _context), do: {:error, "unrecognized data"}
end

defmodule Demo.NoopAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "noop",
    description: "Does nothing, returns empty result",
    schema: []

  def run(_params, _context), do: {:ok, %{}}
end

defmodule Demo.AccumulatorAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "accumulator",
    description: "Stores a tag value",
    schema: [
      tag: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Tag to store"]
    ]

  def run(%{tag: tag}, _context), do: {:ok, %{tag: tag}}
end

# Jido.Agent generates functions with iex> doctests that Livebook tries to run.
# This macro suppresses them by overriding with @doc false.
defmodule Demo.Helpers do
  defmacro suppress_agent_doctests do
    quote do
      @doc false
      def plugins, do: super()
      @doc false
      def capabilities, do: super()
      @doc false
      def signal_types, do: super()
    end
  end
end

Kino.Markdown.new("**All demo actions defined.**")
```

## Demo 1: Your First Workflow (ETL Pipeline)

The simplest Workflow pattern -- a linear 3-step FSM using `run_sync`.

Each step's result is **scoped** under its state name in the accumulated context.
So after the `extract` step, its output lives at `ctx[:extract]`. The `transform`
step receives the full context and reads from `ctx[:extract][:records]`.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> extract
    extract --> transform : ok
    transform --> load : ok
    load --> done : ok
    extract --> failed : error
    transform --> failed : error
    load --> failed : error
```

```elixir
defmodule Demo.ETLWorkflow do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Workflow,
    name: "etl_pipeline",
    description: "Extract, transform, load pipeline",
    nodes: %{
      extract: Demo.ExtractAction,
      transform: Demo.TransformAction,
      load: Demo.LoadAction
    },
    transitions: %{
      {:extract, :ok} => :transform,
      {:transform, :ok} => :load,
      {:load, :ok} => :done,
      {:_, :error} => :failed
    },
    initial: :extract

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

agent = Demo.ETLWorkflow.new()
{:ok, ctx} = Demo.ETLWorkflow.run_sync(agent, %{source: "customer_db"})

results = [
  {"Extract step", :extract, ctx[:extract]},
  {"Transform step", :transform, ctx[:transform]},
  {"Load step", :load, ctx[:load]}
]

header =
  Kino.Markdown.new("""
  ### ETL Pipeline Results

  Each step's output is scoped under its state name. The transform step
  read from `extract.records` and uppercased the source field. The load step read
  from `transform.records` and counted 2 loaded records.
  """)

step_widgets =
  Enum.flat_map(results, fn {label, key, data} ->
    [
      Kino.Markdown.new("**#{label}** (`ctx[:#{key}]`)"),
      Kino.Tree.new(data)
    ]
  end)

Kino.Layout.grid([header | step_widgets], columns: 1)
```

## Demo 2: Branching Workflows (Custom Outcomes)

Actions can return custom outcomes beyond `:ok` and `:error`. When an action returns
`{:ok, result, :custom_outcome}`, the FSM transitions on that custom outcome.

This lets you build quality gates, validation pipelines, and retry logic directly
in the FSM structure.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> validate
    validate --> process : ok
    validate --> handle_invalid : invalid
    validate --> retry_step : retry
    process --> done : ok
    handle_invalid --> done : ok
    retry_step --> done : ok
    validate --> failed : error
```

```elixir
defmodule Demo.BranchingWorkflow do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Workflow,
    name: "quality_gate",
    description: "Validation with outcome-driven branching",
    nodes: %{
      validate: Demo.ValidateOutcomeAction,
      process: Demo.NoopAction,
      handle_invalid: Demo.NoopAction,
      retry_step: Demo.NoopAction
    },
    transitions: %{
      {:validate, :ok} => :process,
      {:validate, :invalid} => :handle_invalid,
      {:validate, :retry} => :retry_step,
      {:process, :ok} => :done,
      {:handle_invalid, :ok} => :done,
      {:retry_step, :ok} => :done,
      {:_, :error} => :failed
    },
    initial: :validate

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

run_branch = fn data ->
  agent = Demo.BranchingWorkflow.new()
  {:ok, ctx} = Demo.BranchingWorkflow.run_sync(agent, %{data: data})
  ctx
end

valid_ctx = run_branch.("valid")
invalid_ctx = run_branch.("invalid")
retry_ctx = run_branch.("retry")

tab = fn _, input, path, ctx_data ->
  Kino.Layout.grid([
    Kino.Markdown.new("**Input**: `%{data: \"#{input}\"}` | **Path**: #{path}"),
    Kino.Markdown.new("**Validate result:**"),
    Kino.Tree.new(ctx_data)
  ], columns: 1)
end

Kino.Layout.tabs(
  "valid (-> process)":
    tab.("valid", "valid", "validate -> process -> done", valid_ctx[:validate]),
  "invalid (-> handle_invalid)":
    tab.("invalid", "invalid", "validate -> handle_invalid -> done", invalid_ctx[:validate]),
  "retry (-> retry_step)":
    tab.("retry", "retry", "validate -> retry_step -> done", retry_ctx[:validate])
)
```

## Demo 3: Parallel Execution (FanOutNode)

FanOutNode executes multiple branches concurrently and merges results.
It appears as a single state in the FSM but internally spawns tasks for each branch.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> parallel
    parallel --> finalize : ok
    finalize --> done : ok
    parallel --> failed : error
```

```elixir
defmodule Demo.FanOutWorkflow do
  @moduledoc false
  alias Jido.Composer.Node.{ActionNode, FanOutNode}

  {:ok, add_node} = ActionNode.new(Demo.AddAction)
  {:ok, echo_node} = ActionNode.new(Demo.EchoAction)

  {:ok, fan_out} =
    FanOutNode.new(
      name: "parallel_compute",
      branches: [math: add_node, echo: echo_node]
    )

  use Jido.Composer.Workflow,
    name: "fan_out_demo",
    description: "Parallel execution with FanOutNode",
    nodes: %{
      parallel: fan_out,
      finalize: Demo.NoopAction
    },
    transitions: %{
      {:parallel, :ok} => :finalize,
      {:finalize, :ok} => :done,
      {:_, :error} => :failed
    },
    initial: :parallel

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

agent = Demo.FanOutWorkflow.new()
{:ok, ctx} = Demo.FanOutWorkflow.run_sync(agent, %{value: 10.0, amount: 5.0, message: "hello"})

Kino.Layout.grid([
  Kino.Markdown.new("""
  ### Parallel Execution Results

  Both branches ran concurrently. Results are scoped under `parallel` -> branch name.
  """),
  Kino.Markdown.new("**Math branch** (`ctx[:parallel][:math]`) — 10.0 + 5.0 = #{ctx[:parallel][:math][:result]}"),
  Kino.Tree.new(ctx[:parallel][:math]),
  Kino.Markdown.new("**Echo branch** (`ctx[:parallel][:echo]`) — echoed: \"#{ctx[:parallel][:echo][:echoed]}\""),
  Kino.Tree.new(ctx[:parallel][:echo])
], columns: 1)
```

## Demo 4: Human-in-the-Loop (Suspend/Resume)

HumanNode pauses the workflow and emits a `SuspendForHuman` directive.
The workflow waits for an `ApprovalResponse` before continuing.

We'll visualize the FSM state in real-time using Mermaid diagrams that
highlight the current state.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> prepare
    prepare --> approval : ok
    approval --> deploy : approved
    approval --> failed : rejected
    deploy --> done : ok
```

````elixir
alias Jido.Agent.Directive
alias Jido.Agent.Strategy.State, as: StratState
alias Jido.Composer.Directive.SuspendForHuman
alias Jido.Composer.HITL.{ApprovalRequest, ApprovalResponse}
alias Jido.Composer.Node.HumanNode

defmodule Demo.DeployWorkflow do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Workflow,
    name: "deploy_pipeline",
    description: "Deployment pipeline with human approval gate",
    nodes: %{
      prepare: Demo.AccumulatorAction,
      approval: %HumanNode{
        name: "deploy_gate",
        description: "Approve deployment to production",
        prompt: "Deploy to production?",
        allowed_responses: [:approved, :rejected]
      },
      deploy: Demo.NoopAction
    },
    transitions: %{
      {:prepare, :ok} => :approval,
      {:approval, :approved} => :deploy,
      {:approval, :rejected} => :failed,
      {:deploy, :ok} => :done,
      {:_, :error} => :failed
    },
    initial: :prepare

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

# Helper: render Mermaid FSM diagram with current state highlighted
fence = "```"

fsm_diagram = fn current_state ->
  """
  #{fence}mermaid
  stateDiagram-v2
      [*] --> prepare
      prepare --> approval : ok
      approval --> deploy : approved
      approval --> failed : rejected
      deploy --> done : ok

      classDef active fill:#f96,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px
      class #{current_state} active
  #{fence}
  """
end

# Helper: execute directives until SuspendForHuman or done (recursive loop)
defmodule Demo.DirectiveRunner do
  def run(_agent_module, agent, []), do: {agent, []}

  def run(agent_module, agent, [directive | rest]) do
    alias Jido.Agent.Directive
    alias Jido.Composer.Directive.SuspendForHuman

    case directive do
      %Directive.RunInstruction{instruction: instr, result_action: result_action} ->
        payload =
          case Jido.Exec.run(instr.action, instr.params, %{}, timeout: 0) do
            {:ok, result} -> %{status: :ok, result: result}
            {:ok, result, outcome} -> %{status: :ok, result: result, outcome: outcome}
            {:error, reason} -> %{status: :error, reason: reason}
          end

        {agent, new_directives} = agent_module.cmd(agent, {result_action, payload})
        run(agent_module, agent, new_directives ++ rest)

      %SuspendForHuman{} = suspend ->
        {agent, [suspend | rest]}

      _ ->
        run(agent_module, agent, rest)
    end
  end
end

# State frame for live FSM visualization
state_frame = Kino.Frame.new()
log_frame = Kino.Frame.new()

# Step 1: Start the workflow
Kino.Frame.render(state_frame, Kino.Markdown.new(fsm_diagram.("prepare")))
Kino.Frame.render(log_frame, Kino.Markdown.new("**Starting workflow...**"))

agent = Demo.DeployWorkflow.new()
{agent, directives} = Demo.DeployWorkflow.run(agent, %{tag: "deploy-v2.1"})

# Step 2: Execute until we hit the HumanNode
{agent, remaining} = Demo.DirectiveRunner.run(Demo.DeployWorkflow, agent, directives)

[%SuspendForHuman{approval_request: request} | _] = remaining

Kino.Frame.render(state_frame, Kino.Markdown.new(fsm_diagram.("approval")))

Kino.Frame.render(
  log_frame,
  Kino.Markdown.new("""
  **Workflow suspended at approval gate.**

  - Prompt: "#{request.prompt}"
  - Allowed responses: #{inspect(request.allowed_responses)}
  - Request ID: `#{request.id}`
  """)
)

# Step 3: Show approval form
form =
  Kino.Control.form(
    [
      decision:
        Kino.Input.select("Decision", [
          {:approved, "Approve"},
          {:rejected, "Reject"}
        ])
    ],
    submit: "Submit Decision"
  )

Kino.render(Kino.Layout.grid([state_frame, log_frame, form], columns: 1))

# Step 4: Wait for form submission and resume
decision_data = Kino.Control.stream(form) |> Enum.take(1) |> List.first()
decision = decision_data.data.decision

{:ok, response} =
  ApprovalResponse.new(
    request_id: request.id,
    decision: decision,
    respondent: "livebook_user",
    comment: "Decision made via Livebook"
  )

{agent, directives} =
  Demo.DeployWorkflow.cmd(agent, {:hitl_response, Map.from_struct(response)})

# Execute remaining directives
{agent, _} = Demo.DirectiveRunner.run(Demo.DeployWorkflow, agent, directives)

# Step 5: Show final state
strat = StratState.get(agent)
final_state = strat.machine.status

Kino.Frame.render(state_frame, Kino.Markdown.new(fsm_diagram.(final_state)))

Kino.Frame.render(
  log_frame,
  Kino.Markdown.new("""
  **Workflow #{if final_state == :done, do: "completed successfully", else: "was rejected"}.**

  - Decision: `#{decision}`
  - Final state: `#{final_state}`
  - HITL response in context: `#{inspect(strat.machine.context[:hitl_response][:decision])}`
  """)
)
````

## Demo 5: LLM Orchestrator

The Orchestrator uses an LLM in a **ReAct loop** to decide which tools to call:

1. LLM receives the query + tool descriptions
2. LLM reasons and selects a tool with arguments
3. Tool executes, result is fed back to LLM
4. LLM either calls another tool or produces a final answer

This requires the `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` configured in Setup.

```elixir
defmodule Demo.ToolOrchestrator do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Orchestrator,
    name: "demo_assistant",
    description: "A helpful assistant with math and echo tools",
    model: "anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
    nodes: [Demo.AddAction, Demo.EchoAction],
    system_prompt: """
    You are a helpful assistant with access to math and echo tools.
    Use the add tool for arithmetic. Use the echo tool to repeat messages.
    Always use tools when they are relevant to the user's request.
    """,
    max_iterations: 5

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

agent = Demo.ToolOrchestrator.new()
{:ok, answer} = Demo.ToolOrchestrator.query_sync(agent, "What is 5 + 3?")

Kino.Markdown.new("""
### Orchestrator Result

**Query**: "What is 5 + 3?"

**Answer**: #{answer}

---

The LLM saw `add` and `echo` as available tools. It chose `add` with
`%{value: 5.0, amount: 3.0}`, got back `%{result: 8.0}`, and produced
the final answer.
""")
```

## Demo 6: Composition (Workflow as Orchestrator Tool)

You can wrap a Workflow in an Action, making it available as a tool for an Orchestrator.
The LLM sees it as a single callable tool. When invoked, the full FSM runs internally
and returns the accumulated context.

```elixir
# Wrap the ETL Workflow in an Action so the orchestrator can call it as a tool.
# query_sync runs in-process, so we use run_sync to execute the workflow inline.
defmodule Demo.ETLToolAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "etl_pipeline",
    description: "Runs an ETL pipeline: extracts data from a source, transforms records by uppercasing, and loads them. Returns the full pipeline results.",
    schema: [
      source: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Data source identifier"]
    ]

  def run(%{source: source}, _context) do
    agent = Demo.ETLWorkflow.new()

    case Demo.ETLWorkflow.run_sync(agent, %{source: source}) do
      {:ok, ctx} -> {:ok, ctx}
      {:error, reason} -> {:error, reason}
    end
  end
end

defmodule Demo.ComposedOrchestrator do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Orchestrator,
    name: "composed_assistant",
    description: "An assistant that can run ETL pipelines and echo messages",
    model: "anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
    nodes: [Demo.EchoAction, Demo.ETLToolAction],
    system_prompt: """
    You can run ETL pipelines and echo messages.
    When asked to process data, use the etl_pipeline tool with a source parameter.
    When asked to echo or repeat something, use the echo tool.
    """,
    max_iterations: 5

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

agent = Demo.ComposedOrchestrator.new()

{:ok, answer} =
  Demo.ComposedOrchestrator.query_sync(
    agent,
    "Run the ETL pipeline on the orders database and tell me what happened."
  )

Kino.Markdown.new("""
### Composed Orchestrator Result

**Query**: "Run the ETL pipeline on the orders database and tell me what happened."

**Answer**: #{answer}

---

`Demo.ETLToolAction` wraps the 3-step Workflow as a plain Action. The LLM sees
`etl_pipeline` as a tool. When called with `source: "orders"`, the full FSM runs
internally (extract -> transform -> load) and the accumulated context is returned.
""")
```

## Demo 7: AgentNode (Nested Agent in a Workflow)

**AgentNode** wraps a `Jido.Agent` (including orchestrators) as a workflow step.
The workflow's FSM treats it like any other node -- when reached, it spawns the
child agent, sends context, and awaits the result.

This lets you nest LLM-driven orchestrators inside deterministic workflows,
combining the predictability of FSMs with the flexibility of LLM reasoning.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> gather_input
    gather_input --> analyze : ok
    analyze --> format_output : ok
    format_output --> done : ok
    gather_input --> failed : error
    analyze --> failed : error
    format_output --> failed : error

    note right of analyze
        This step is an AgentNode wrapping
        an LLM Orchestrator that reasons
        about the input data.
    end note
```

```elixir
# Step 1: Define actions for the workflow's deterministic steps
defmodule Demo.GatherInputAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "gather_input",
    description: "Gathers and validates input data for analysis",
    schema: [
      topic: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Topic to analyze"],
      depth: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Analysis depth: brief or detailed"]
    ]

  def run(%{topic: topic} = params, _context) do
    depth = Map.get(params, :depth, "brief")
    {:ok, %{topic: topic, depth: depth, gathered_at: DateTime.utc_now() |> to_string()}}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.FormatOutputAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "format_output",
    description: "Formats the analysis results into a structured report",
    schema: [
      analyze: [type: :map, required: false, doc: "Results from the analysis step"]
    ]

  def run(params, _context) do
    analysis = params[:analyze] || %{}
    {:ok, %{report: "## Analysis Report\n\n#{inspect(analysis, pretty: true)}", formatted: true}}
  end
end

# Step 2: Define the inner orchestrator agent that will be used via AgentNode
defmodule Demo.AnalysisOrchestrator do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Orchestrator,
    name: "analysis_agent",
    description: "Analyzes a topic using available tools",
    model: "anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
    nodes: [Demo.AddAction, Demo.EchoAction],
    system_prompt: """
    You are an analysis assistant. When given a topic, provide a brief analysis.
    Use the echo tool to record your key findings.
    Use the add tool if any numeric analysis is needed.
    Be concise and provide your final answer as a structured summary.
    """,
    max_iterations: 5

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

# Step 3: Wrap the orchestrator call as an Action so we can use it as a workflow tool.
# This is the pattern for nesting an orchestrator inside a workflow step.
defmodule Demo.AnalyzeAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "analyze",
    description: "Runs an LLM-powered analysis orchestrator on the gathered input",
    schema: [
      gather_input: [type: :map, required: false, doc: "Results from gather_input step"]
    ]

  def run(params, _context) do
    input = params[:gather_input] || %{}
    topic = input[:topic] || "unknown topic"
    depth = input[:depth] || "brief"

    agent = Demo.AnalysisOrchestrator.new()

    case Demo.AnalysisOrchestrator.query_sync(
           agent,
           "Analyze the topic '#{topic}' at #{depth} depth. Provide key points."
         ) do
      {:ok, answer} ->
        {:ok, %{topic: topic, analysis: answer, depth: depth}}

      {:error, reason} ->
        {:error, "Analysis failed: #{inspect(reason)}"}
    end
  end
end

# Step 4: Build the workflow with the orchestrator-backed step
defmodule Demo.AnalysisWorkflow do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Workflow,
    name: "analysis_pipeline",
    description: "Deterministic pipeline with LLM analysis step",
    nodes: %{
      gather_input: Demo.GatherInputAction,
      analyze: Demo.AnalyzeAction,
      format_output: Demo.FormatOutputAction
    },
    transitions: %{
      {:gather_input, :ok} => :analyze,
      {:analyze, :ok} => :format_output,
      {:format_output, :ok} => :done,
      {:_, :error} => :failed
    },
    initial: :gather_input

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

# Step 5: Run the workflow
frame = Kino.Frame.new() |> Kino.render()
Kino.Frame.render(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("**Running analysis pipeline...**\n\nThe workflow will:\n1. Gather input (deterministic)\n2. Run LLM orchestrator to analyze (LLM-driven)\n3. Format output (deterministic)"))

agent = Demo.AnalysisWorkflow.new()
{:ok, ctx} = Demo.AnalysisWorkflow.run_sync(agent, %{topic: "composable agent architectures", depth: "brief"})

Kino.Frame.render(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("**Pipeline complete!**"))

Kino.Layout.tabs(
  "Gathered Input": Kino.Layout.grid([
    Kino.Markdown.new("**Step 1** -- Deterministic input gathering"),
    Kino.Tree.new(ctx[:gather_input])
  ], columns: 1),
  "LLM Analysis": Kino.Layout.grid([
    Kino.Markdown.new("**Step 2** -- LLM orchestrator produced this analysis:"),
    Kino.Markdown.new(ctx[:analyze][:analysis] || "_No analysis_")
  ], columns: 1),
  "Formatted Report": Kino.Layout.grid([
    Kino.Markdown.new("**Step 3** -- Final formatted output"),
    Kino.Tree.new(ctx[:format_output])
  ], columns: 1)
)
```

## Demo 8: Multi-Agent Domain Modeling Pipeline

This demo reproduces the **automated domain modeler** pattern: three specialist
orchestrators (Researcher, Architect, Evaluator) coordinated by a deterministic
workflow with a quality-driven refinement loop.

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    Input["User Input<br/>(domain description)"]
    Input --> Research

    subgraph Research["Phase 1: Research"]
        RA["ResearcherOrchestrator<br/>Tools: analyze_domain, extract_concepts"]
    end

    Research --> Architecture

    subgraph Architecture["Phase 2: Architecture"]
        AA["ArchitectOrchestrator<br/>Tools: identify_entities, define_aggregates"]
    end

    Architecture --> Evaluation

    subgraph Evaluation["Phase 3: Evaluation"]
        EA["EvaluatorOrchestrator<br/>Tools: assess_quality, suggest_refinements"]
    end

    Evaluation -->|"quality >= threshold"| Results["Final Domain Model"]
    Evaluation -->|"quality < threshold"| Architecture
```

### Define Domain Modeling Tools

```elixir
# -- Research Tools --

defmodule Demo.AnalyzeDomainAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "analyze_domain",
    description: "Analyzes a domain description to identify key business areas, stakeholders, and core workflows. Returns a structured analysis of the domain.",
    schema: [
      domain_description: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "The domain description to analyze"],
      focus_area: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Optional area to focus the analysis on"]
    ]

  def run(%{domain_description: desc} = params, _context) do
    focus = Map.get(params, :focus_area, "general")
    {:ok, %{
      domain: desc,
      focus: focus,
      analyzed: true,
      note: "Domain analysis complete for focus: #{focus}"
    }}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.ExtractConceptsAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "extract_concepts",
    description: "Extracts domain concepts, relationships, and business rules from analyzed domain data. Returns structured concept lists.",
    schema: [
      analysis: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Domain analysis text to extract concepts from"],
      category: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Category filter: entities, events, rules, or all"]
    ]

  def run(%{analysis: analysis} = params, _context) do
    category = Map.get(params, :category, "all")
    {:ok, %{
      source: analysis,
      category: category,
      extracted: true,
      note: "Concepts extracted for category: #{category}"
    }}
  end
end

# -- Architecture Tools --

defmodule Demo.IdentifyEntitiesAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "identify_entities",
    description: "Classifies domain concepts into entities (with lifecycle), value objects (immutable), and domain events. Returns structured classification.",
    schema: [
      concepts: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Concepts to classify into DDD tactical patterns"],
      domain: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Domain context for classification"]
    ]

  def run(%{concepts: concepts} = params, _context) do
    domain = Map.get(params, :domain, "general")
    {:ok, %{
      input_concepts: concepts,
      domain: domain,
      classified: true,
      note: "Entity classification complete for domain: #{domain}"
    }}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.DefineAggregatesAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "define_aggregates",
    description: "Groups classified entities into aggregates with roots, invariants, commands, and events. Defines bounded context boundaries.",
    schema: [
      entities: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Classified entities to group into aggregates"],
      refinement_hints: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Hints from evaluator for refinement"]
    ]

  def run(%{entities: entities} = params, _context) do
    hints = Map.get(params, :refinement_hints, "none")
    {:ok, %{
      input_entities: entities,
      refinement_hints: hints,
      aggregates_defined: true,
      note: "Aggregates defined#{if hints != "none", do: " with refinement hints", else: ""}"
    }}
  end
end

# -- Evaluation Tools --

defmodule Demo.AssessQualityAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "assess_quality",
    description: "Scores a domain model on accuracy, completeness, clarity, and relevance. Returns dimensional scores and an overall quality score from 0.0 to 1.0.",
    schema: [
      domain_model: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Domain model to assess"],
      criteria: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Specific criteria to evaluate"]
    ]

  def run(%{domain_model: model} = params, _context) do
    criteria = Map.get(params, :criteria, "standard DDD")
    {:ok, %{
      model_assessed: model,
      criteria: criteria,
      assessed: true,
      note: "Quality assessment complete with criteria: #{criteria}"
    }}
  end
end

defmodule Demo.SuggestRefinementsAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "suggest_refinements",
    description: "Identifies issues and suggests specific improvements for the domain model. Returns prioritized refinement suggestions for the architect.",
    schema: [
      assessment: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Quality assessment to generate refinements for"],
      domain_model: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "The domain model being refined"]
    ]

  def run(%{assessment: assessment} = params, _context) do
    model = Map.get(params, :domain_model, "")
    {:ok, %{
      assessment_input: assessment,
      model_input: model,
      refinements_suggested: true,
      note: "Refinement suggestions generated"
    }}
  end
end

Kino.Markdown.new("**Domain modeling tools defined.**")
```

### Define Specialist Orchestrators

```elixir
defmodule Demo.ResearcherOrchestrator do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Orchestrator,
    name: "domain_researcher",
    description: "Researches a domain to extract key concepts, relationships, and business rules",
    model: "anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
    nodes: [Demo.AnalyzeDomainAction, Demo.ExtractConceptsAction],
    system_prompt: """
    You are a domain research specialist. Your job is to thoroughly analyze a domain
    description and extract structured knowledge.

    Follow these steps:
    1. Use analyze_domain to understand the business areas and workflows
    2. Use extract_concepts to identify entities, events, and business rules
    3. Provide a comprehensive research summary as your final answer

    Your final answer MUST be a structured research report including:
    - Key domain concepts identified
    - Important business rules
    - Relationships between concepts
    - Recommendations for the domain architect
    """,
    max_iterations: 8

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

defmodule Demo.ArchitectOrchestrator do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Orchestrator,
    name: "domain_architect",
    description: "Designs DDD-compliant domain models from research findings",
    model: "anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
    nodes: [Demo.IdentifyEntitiesAction, Demo.DefineAggregatesAction],
    system_prompt: """
    You are a Domain-Driven Design architect. Your job is to design a domain model
    from research findings.

    Follow these steps:
    1. Use identify_entities to classify concepts into entities, value objects, and events
    2. Use define_aggregates to group entities into aggregates with invariants

    If you receive refinement hints from a previous evaluation, address them specifically.

    Your final answer MUST include:
    - Bounded Contexts with their responsibilities
    - Aggregates with roots, commands, events, and invariants
    - Entity and value object classifications
    - A ubiquitous language glossary
    """,
    max_iterations: 8

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

defmodule Demo.EvaluatorOrchestrator do
  @moduledoc false
  use Jido.Composer.Orchestrator,
    name: "ddd_evaluator",
    description: "Evaluates domain model quality and suggests refinements",
    model: "anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
    nodes: [Demo.AssessQualityAction, Demo.SuggestRefinementsAction],
    system_prompt: """
    You are a DDD quality evaluator. Your job is to assess a domain model's quality
    and provide actionable refinement suggestions.

    Follow these steps:
    1. Use assess_quality to score the model on accuracy, completeness, clarity, and relevance
    2. Use suggest_refinements to identify specific improvements

    Your final answer MUST be structured as:
    - QUALITY_SCORE: [a number between 0.0 and 1.0]
    - Dimensional scores (accuracy, completeness, clarity, relevance)
    - Issues found (with severity: high/medium/low)
    - Specific refinement suggestions for the architect
    - Overall assessment summary
    """,
    max_iterations: 8

  require Demo.Helpers
  Demo.Helpers.suppress_agent_doctests()
end

Kino.Markdown.new("**Specialist orchestrators defined:** Researcher, Architect, Evaluator")
```

### Define Pipeline Actions

```elixir
# Wrap each orchestrator call as a pipeline action

defmodule Demo.ResearchAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "research_phase",
    description: "Runs the research orchestrator on a domain description",
    schema: [
      domain_description: [type: :string, required: true, doc: "Domain to research"]
    ]

  def run(%{domain_description: desc}, _context) do
    agent = Demo.ResearcherOrchestrator.new()

    case Demo.ResearcherOrchestrator.query_sync(agent,
           "Research the following domain and provide a comprehensive analysis:\n\n#{desc}"
         ) do
      {:ok, answer} -> {:ok, %{research: answer, domain: desc}}
      {:error, reason} -> {:error, "Research failed: #{inspect(reason)}"}
    end
  end
end

defmodule Demo.ArchitectAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "architect_phase",
    description: "Runs the architect orchestrator to design a domain model",
    schema: [
      research_phase: [type: :map, required: false, doc: "Research results"],
      domain_description: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Original domain description"],
      refinement_hints: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Hints from previous evaluation"]
    ]

  def run(params, _context) do
    research = get_in(params, [:research_phase, :research]) || ""
    domain = get_in(params, [:research_phase, :domain]) || params[:domain_description] || ""
    hints = params[:refinement_hints] || ""

    query = """
    Design a DDD domain model based on these research findings:

    DOMAIN: #{domain}

    RESEARCH:
    #{research}
    #{if hints != "", do: "\nREFINEMENT HINTS FROM EVALUATOR:\n#{hints}", else: ""}
    """

    agent = Demo.ArchitectOrchestrator.new()

    case Demo.ArchitectOrchestrator.query_sync(agent, query) do
      {:ok, answer} -> {:ok, %{domain_model: answer, domain: domain}}
      {:error, reason} -> {:error, "Architecture failed: #{inspect(reason)}"}
    end
  end
end

defmodule Demo.EvaluateAction do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "evaluate_phase",
    description: "Runs the evaluator orchestrator to assess domain model quality",
    schema: [
      architect_phase: [type: :map, required: false, doc: "Architect results"],
      domain_description: [type: :string, required: false, doc: "Original domain description"]
    ]

  def run(params, _context) do
    model = get_in(params, [:architect_phase, :domain_model]) || ""
    domain = get_in(params, [:architect_phase, :domain]) || params[:domain_description] || ""

    query = """
    Evaluate this domain model for DDD quality:

    DOMAIN: #{domain}

    DOMAIN MODEL:
    #{model}

    Score the model between 0.0 and 1.0. Include QUALITY_SCORE: [score] in your answer.
    """

    agent = Demo.EvaluatorOrchestrator.new()

    case Demo.EvaluatorOrchestrator.query_sync(agent, query) do
      {:ok, answer} ->
        # Extract quality score from answer
        score = extract_quality_score(answer)
        {:ok, %{evaluation: answer, quality_score: score, domain_model: model}}

      {:error, reason} ->
        {:error, "Evaluation failed: #{inspect(reason)}"}
    end
  end

  defp extract_quality_score(text) do
    case Regex.run(~r/QUALITY_SCORE:\s*([\d.]+)/i, text) do
      [_, score_str] ->
        case Float.parse(score_str) do
          {score, _} -> min(max(score, 0.0), 1.0)
          :error -> 0.5
        end
      nil -> 0.5
    end
  end
end

Kino.Markdown.new("**Pipeline actions defined.**")
```

### Run the Pipeline

```elixir
# Configuration
domain_input =
  Kino.Input.textarea("Domain Description",
    default: """
    An online veterinary clinic management system that handles pet owner registration,
    pet profiles with medical history, appointment scheduling with veterinarians,
    medical record keeping including diagnoses and prescriptions,
    and billing with payment processing.
    """
  )

threshold_input =
  Kino.Input.range("Quality Threshold", min: 0.5, max: 1.0, step: 0.05, default: 0.7)

iterations_input = Kino.Input.number("Max Refinement Iterations", default: 2)

Kino.Layout.grid([domain_input, threshold_input, iterations_input], columns: 1)
```

```elixir
domain_description = Kino.Input.read(domain_input)
quality_threshold = Kino.Input.read(threshold_input)
max_iterations = Kino.Input.read(iterations_input)

# Progress tracking
frame = Kino.Frame.new() |> Kino.render()
results_frame = Kino.Frame.new() |> Kino.render()

log = fn msg ->
  Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new(msg))
end

log.("### Domain Modeling Pipeline\n")
log.("**Domain:** #{String.slice(domain_description, 0, 100)}...\n")
log.("**Quality threshold:** #{quality_threshold} | **Max iterations:** #{max_iterations}\n")
log.("---\n")

# Phase 1: Research
log.("**Phase 1: Research** -- Starting researcher orchestrator...")

research_start = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond)
research_agent = Demo.ResearcherOrchestrator.new()

research_result =
  Demo.ResearcherOrchestrator.query_sync(
    research_agent,
    "Research the following domain and provide a comprehensive analysis:\n\n#{domain_description}"
  )

research_duration = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond) - research_start

case research_result do
  {:ok, research} ->
    log.("Research complete (#{research_duration}ms)\n---\n")

    # Phase 2+3: Architecture + Evaluation Loop
    final_result =
      Enum.reduce_while(1..max_iterations, %{domain_model: nil, evaluation: nil, iteration: 0, hints: ""}, fn iteration, acc ->
        # Architecture Phase
        log.("**Phase 2: Architecture** (iteration #{iteration}/#{max_iterations}) -- Starting architect...")

        arch_start = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond)
        arch_agent = Demo.ArchitectOrchestrator.new()

        arch_query = """
        Design a DDD domain model based on these research findings:

        DOMAIN: #{domain_description}

        RESEARCH:
        #{research}
        #{if acc.hints != "", do: "\nREFINEMENT HINTS FROM EVALUATOR:\n#{acc.hints}", else: ""}
        """

        case Demo.ArchitectOrchestrator.query_sync(arch_agent, arch_query) do
          {:ok, domain_model} ->
            arch_duration = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond) - arch_start
            log.("Architecture complete (#{arch_duration}ms)\n")

            # Evaluation Phase
            log.("**Phase 3: Evaluation** (iteration #{iteration}) -- Starting evaluator...")

            eval_start = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond)
            eval_agent = Demo.EvaluatorOrchestrator.new()

            eval_query = """
            Evaluate this domain model for DDD quality:

            DOMAIN: #{domain_description}

            DOMAIN MODEL:
            #{domain_model}

            Score the model between 0.0 and 1.0. Start your response with QUALITY_SCORE: [score]
            """

            case Demo.EvaluatorOrchestrator.query_sync(eval_agent, eval_query) do
              {:ok, evaluation} ->
                eval_duration = System.monotonic_time(:millisecond) - eval_start

                # Extract quality score
                score =
                  case Regex.run(~r/QUALITY_SCORE:\s*([\d.]+)/i, evaluation) do
                    [_, s] ->
                      case Float.parse(s) do
                        {v, _} -> min(max(v, 0.0), 1.0)
                        :error -> 0.5
                      end
                    nil -> 0.5
                  end

                log.("Evaluation complete (#{eval_duration}ms) -- Quality: **#{Float.round(score * 100, 1)}%**\n")

                if score >= quality_threshold do
                  log.("Quality threshold met! (#{Float.round(score * 100, 1)}% >= #{Float.round(quality_threshold * 100, 1)}%)\n---\n")
                  {:halt, %{domain_model: domain_model, evaluation: evaluation, quality_score: score, iteration: iteration, research: research}}
                else
                  log.("Below threshold (#{Float.round(score * 100, 1)}% < #{Float.round(quality_threshold * 100, 1)}%) -- refining...\n---\n")
                  if iteration == max_iterations do
                    log.("**Max iterations reached.** Using best result.\n---\n")
                    {:halt, %{domain_model: domain_model, evaluation: evaluation, quality_score: score, iteration: iteration, research: research}}
                  else
                    {:cont, %{acc | domain_model: domain_model, evaluation: evaluation, iteration: iteration, hints: evaluation}}
                  end
                end

              {:error, reason} ->
                log.("Evaluation failed: #{inspect(reason)}\n")
                {:halt, %{domain_model: domain_model, evaluation: "Evaluation failed", quality_score: 0.0, iteration: iteration, research: research}}
            end

          {:error, reason} ->
            log.("Architecture failed: #{inspect(reason)}\n")
            {:halt, %{domain_model: "Architecture failed", evaluation: nil, quality_score: 0.0, iteration: iteration, research: research}}
        end
      end)

    log.("**Pipeline complete!**\n")

    # Display results in tabs
    Kino.Frame.render(results_frame,
      Kino.Layout.tabs(
        "Domain Model": Kino.Markdown.new("""
        # Domain Model

        #{final_result[:domain_model] || "_No model produced_"}
        """),
        "Research": Kino.Markdown.new("""
        # Research Report

        #{final_result[:research] || "_No research_"}
        """),
        "Evaluation": Kino.Markdown.new("""
        # Evaluation

        **Quality Score:** #{Float.round((final_result[:quality_score] || 0.0) * 100, 1)}%
        **Iterations:** #{final_result[:iteration] || 0}

        #{final_result[:evaluation] || "_No evaluation_"}
        """),
        "Metrics": Kino.Markdown.new("""
        # Pipeline Metrics

        | Metric | Value |
        |--------|-------|
        | Research Duration | #{research_duration}ms |
        | Quality Score | #{Float.round((final_result[:quality_score] || 0.0) * 100, 1)}% |
        | Iterations | #{final_result[:iteration] || 0} / #{max_iterations} |
        | Quality Threshold | #{Float.round(quality_threshold * 100, 1)}% |
        """)
      )
    )

  {:error, reason} ->
    log.("**Research failed:** #{inspect(reason)}")
end

:ok
```

## Conclusion

This notebook demonstrated the full range of composition patterns in **jido_composer**:

| Demo               | Pattern                 | Key Concept                               |
| ------------------ | ----------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| 1. ETL Pipeline    | Workflow                | Linear FSM, scoped context accumulation   |
| 2. Quality Gate    | Workflow                | Custom outcomes for branching transitions |
| 3. Fan-Out         | Workflow                | Parallel execution with FanOutNode        |
| 4. Deploy Pipeline | Workflow + HITL         | Suspend/resume with human approval        |
| 5. Tool Assistant  | Orchestrator            | LLM-driven ReAct loop with tools          |
| 6. Composed        | Orchestrator + Workflow | Workflows as tools inside orchestrators   |
| 7. Analysis Agent  | Workflow + AgentNode    | LLM orchestrator nested in workflow step  |
| 8. Domain Modeler  | Multi-Orchestrator      | Three specialist LLM agents in a pipeline |

**Key takeaways:**

* **Workflows** give you deterministic, auditable pipelines with FSM guarantees
* **Orchestrators** give you flexible, LLM-driven composition at runtime
* **Nodes** provide a uniform interface -- actions, workflows, and human gates are all interchangeable
* **AgentNode** lets you nest orchestrators inside workflows, combining FSM predictability with LLM flexibility
* **Multi-agent pipelines** compose specialist orchestrators with quality-driven iteration loops
* **Nesting** is natural -- orchestrators can call workflows, workflows can contain agents, all composable
